f technological, social, and political transformations. This process culminated in the nuclear age, when strategic thinking became "self-referring and self-legitimating" and strategic considerations emerged as "the decisive force in the conduct of the politics of states and blocs." Strategic Thinking addresses many of the themes that preoccupied Windsor throughout his academic career and on which his reflections threw such penetrating light: Soviet strategic thought, arms control, the role of alliances, the guerrilla phenomenon, and the rationality and ethics of nuclear deterrence. The final chapter explores the implications of the end of the Cold War for the future of strategic studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBerdal, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerdal, Mats, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEconomides, Spyros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEconomides, Spyros, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107842510 cprintz978158826048240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978168585512340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781685855123423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781685855123/original  a978-3-11-078425-1  Lynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK